{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2f250749-63dd-407f-a68e-ce1bbc101b69","content":"The directory appears empty, so I'll answer from knowledge:\n\nTo switch from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform with MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0, you just need to **remove** (or set to `false`) the `<UseVSTest>` property in your project file:\n\n```xml\n<!-- Before -->\n<Project Sdk=\"MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0\">\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <TargetFramework>net8.0</TargetFramework>\n    <UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n\n<!-- After -->\n<Project Sdk=\"MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0\">\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <TargetFramework>net8.0</TargetFramework>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n**Key things to know:**\n\n1. **MSTest.Sdk 3.8+ defaults to Microsoft.Testing.Platform**, so simply removing `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>` activates it.\n\n2. **Running tests changes** — use `dotnet test` as before, but the underlying runner is now different. You can also run the test executable directly.\n\n3. **CLI differences** — filter syntax changes from `--filter` to `--filter` with slightly different semantics; use `--help` on the test binary for platform-specific options.\n\n4. **VS integration** — Visual Studio 2022 17.10+ supports Microsoft.Testing.Platform natively. For older versions, add:\n   ```xml\n   <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n   <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n   ```\n\n5. **Review extensions** — if you use custom VSTest adapters/loggers, you'll need their Microsoft.Testing.Platform equivalents (e.g., TRX reporting via `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"40d789bf-22ba-413d-a6cd-6106725aa22c","outputTokens":473,"requestId":"E82C:11815A:2691E3B:290A1E8:6A0493B4"},"id":"4ce5d730-dd0a-4b61-9fa7-3ea5421ded6d","timestamp":"2026-05-13T15:07:47.750Z","parentId":"a32c4cbe-157c-4a83-a571-9bce0b86614f"}
